Bai et al. studied pectin as a biodegradable and biocompatible natural polymer backbone for esterifying with the hydrophobic substance curcumin (Scheme 3
                     ). PEC-CCM conjugates are newly created polymer-drug conjugates with high water solubility. The purpose of the study was to produce PEC-CCM conjugates that are water soluble and to assess their stability, antioxidant activity, and anticancer activity [304]. The MTT [3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5 diphenyltetrazolium bromide] test was used to measure the anticancer activity of PEC-CCM conjugates utilising hepatic cancer cell line (HepG2), breast cancer cell line (MCF-7), cervical cancer cell line (HeLa), and human normal kidney cell line (293 A). It was discovered that PEC-CCM conjugated curcumin was less cytotoxic to normal cells than free curcumin and had a more pronounced inhibitory effect on cancer cells. There is a lot of potential for PEC-CCM conjugates in some food and pharmaceutical applications (Table 2
                     ).

According to Alsakhawy et al., a Naringin-loaded Arabic gum/pectin material was used for developing a wound healing material (Fig. 11
                     ). The results showed that NAR had a sustained drug release with a low haemolytic effect. The ability of NAR-loaded AG/pectin hydrogel to speed up wound healing through the display of antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and anti-apoptotic properties, in addition to induction of angiogenesis, re-epithelialization, and collagen deposition, was more importantly demonstrated in vivo studies carried out on full thickness animal wound models. As a result, NAR-loaded AG/pectin hydrogel may be a promising effective technique in wound healing applications [325]. Some of the wound healing activity and bone regeneration study of pectin listed in table below (Table 3
